## Web Enumeration — Port 80 (nginx)

```bash
# Initial visit — nginx default page, nothing obvious
curl http://<target-ip>/

# Directory brute-force
gobuster dir -u http://<target-ip>/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt

# Findings
/hidden (301)
```

```bash
# Enumerate the subdirectory
gobuster dir -u http://<target-ip>/hidden/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt

# Findings
/whatever (301)
```

```bash
# Page source of /hidden/whatever/ contains a base64 encoded string
curl http://<target-ip>/hidden/whatever/
# Source: <p hidden>ZmxhZ3tmMXJzN19mbDRnfQ==</p>

echo "ZmxhZ3tmMXJzN19mbDRnfQ==" | base64 -d
# flag{f1rs7_fl4g}
```

**Lesson:** Always check page source. Hidden HTML elements (`hidden` attribute, HTML comments, inline base64) are a common CTF and real-world OSCP technique for obscuring data.

