## Web Enumeration — Port 65524 (Apache)

```bash
# Check robots.txt first — always
curl http://<target-ip>:65524/robots.txt

# Contains a hash
User-Agent:*
Disallow:/
a18672860d0510e5ab6699730763b250
```

```bash
# Identify hash type — MD5 (length 32, hex)
# Crack it
echo "a18672860d0510e5ab6699730763b250" > hash.txt
john --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt --format=Raw-MD5 hash.txt
# Result: googlearehistory
```

```bash
# Apache default page source contains additional encoded data
curl http://<target-ip>:65524/
# Source inspection reveals:
# - A flag encoded in base62
# - A hidden hash tied to a non-standard algorithm (easypeasy hash)
```

The easypeasy hash is not in standard John/Hashcat wordlists without the correct ruleset. The hash type is identified via hash-identifier or online tools, and the relevant wordlist (easypeasy.txt) is referenced in the room:

```bash
john --wordlist=easypeasy.txt --format=easypeasy hash.txt
# Result: mypasswordforthatjob
```

