## Key Takeaways

**Always full port scan.** Two of the three services in this room are on ports above 1000. A default nmap scan misses them entirely.

**Check robots.txt and page source immediately.** These are the first two manual checks after landing on any web service — before running any tools.

**Steganography is situational but real.** On the OSCP exam it's rare, but in CTF-style rooms it appears regularly. `steghide`, `binwalk`, and `exiftool` cover the majority of cases.

**Cron writeability is a high-value find.** When you see a cron job running as root, immediately check if the script is writable or if the directory it resides in is writable (directory writability allows dropping a new file with the same name).

```bash
# Key commands for this room type
nmap -p- --min-rate 5000 <ip>                          # Full port scan
gobuster dir -u <url> -w <wordlist>                    # Directory brute-force
hash-identifier <hash>                                  # Identify hash type
steghide extract -sf <image> -p <password>             # Extract hidden data
cat /etc/crontab                                        # Always check cron
ls -la <cron-script>                                   # Check script permissions
```

